Jimmy couldn't have said it any better I feel like he was so raw and real and that needed to be said and heard. We are all still here sitting on our couches going to work, school, seeing family or friends, hugging our children ect. something we really need to embrace and carry the lives that were lost in this terrible event on with us with pride and always give and give back! take a moment to say simply hello to a stranger or just smile as your passing by you never know what a person is feeling or truly going thru and it may just be the smile or hello they truly needed. I know when I am having a hard time or bad day it's always the pure simple things that lift me up or make me smile. Live this life the best you can and love like you are loving for the first time. Tschandra & Family

(Greek. Metanoia); Strong's #3341; This Greek word is a compound word derived from meta, meaning "after" and suggesting some type of change, and nous, meaning "mind."
Thus the word strictly denotes "a change of mind."
But it also connotes remorse for sin, accompanied by a desire to turn away from one's sin, to God, for salvation.
Both John the Baptist and Jesus began their ministries with a call to repentance. (See Matthew 3:2, 4:17)---A call that many of the social outcasts and "sinners" of that day answered, (See Luke 19:1-10),
but that the religious people rejected. (Luke 11:39-44; 18:9-14).
